      </div>
    </a><br>
<div class="card-group">
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-body">
      <p class="card-text">Ransomware is malicious software that infects a computer and prevents users from accessing it until a ransom is paid. </p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
        <div class="card-body">
      <p class="card-text">For numerous years, ransomware versions have been discovered, and they frequently try to extort money from victims by showing an on-screen alert. If you receive an alert, the first thing that should be done is shutting down the machine.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-body">
      <p class="card-text">Malware is occasionally disguised as ransomware, but even after the ransom is paid, the data is not decrypted. This is referred to as wiper malware. For these reasons, it's critical to always have a current offline backup of your most crucial files and data.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
        <div class="card-body">
      <p class="card-text">Phishing is an effort by hackers to steal sensitive information from targeted persons by impersonating genuine organisations, typically via email.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-body">
      <p class="card-text">Public domains, spelling issues within the body of the email or in the email address itself, and online demands for personal information are all things to look out for when identifying phishing emails. Email should not be used to send sensitive information.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div> </div>

<div class="container mt-4">
  <a href="#" class="list-group-item list-group-item-action flex-column align-items-start">
    <div class="d-flex w-100 justify-content-between">
      <h5 class="mb-1">The Use of Personal Devices</h5>
    </div>
  </a><br>
<div class="card-group">
<div class="card">
  <div class="card-body">
    <p class="card-text">Your email account serves as a portal to all your other internet accounts and contains a wealth of personal information. Make a strong password that is distinct from the rest of your accounts. Use three random phrases that signify something to you to create strong and memorable passwords.</p>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="card">
    <div class="card-body">
    <p class="card-text">When you use the same password for all your accounts, you put yourself at risk because if one password is stolen, all your accounts can be accessed. Of course, remembering a lot of passwords might be challenging, but you won't have to if you keep them in your browser.</p>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="card">
  <div class="card-body">
    <p class="card-text">Two-factor authentication is a free security feature that minimises the chance of being hacked by requiring you to submit a second piece of information when logging in, such as receiving an SMS or code. </p>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="card">
    <div class="card-body">
    <p class="card-text">Using the most up-to-date software (including anti-virus software), applications and operating system on your device can increase security instantly.</p>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="card">
    <div class="card-body">
    <p class="card-text">Turn on backup to ensure that you have a copy of all of your crucial data in case it is lost, destroyed, or stolen.</p>
  </div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="container mt-4">
  <a href="#" class="list-group-item list-group-item-action flex-column align-items-start">
    <div class="d-flex w-100 justify-content-between">
      <h5 class="mb-1">Unencrypted File Sharing</h5>
    </div>
  </a><br>
<div class="card-group">
<div class="card">
  <div class="card-body">
    <p class="card-text">If you're transferring files, utilise encrypted Wi-Fi wherever possible. Encryption encrypts the data you submit so that other users can't read it. If "https" appears at the beginning of a website's URL, you know it's encrypted. </p>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="card">
      <div class="card-body">
    <p class="card-text">Whenever feasible, use passwords to secure your information, and avoid joining networks that you are unfamiliar with. Generic network names, such as "freepublicwifi," might be deceptive.</p>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="card">
  <div class="card-body">
    <p class="card-text">Check that the software you're using to exchange files is up to date. Developers invest a lot of time and effort into identifying and fixing security flaws in their software, but it will only function if you keep it up to date. </p>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="card">
      <div class="card-body">
    <p class="card-text">You should not assume that a Wi-Fi hotspot is safe, and you should only use it for as long as you need it. Hackers can steal your identity and swindle anyone whose contacts are kept in your machine if you enter an unencrypted site.</p>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="card">
  <div class="card-body">
    <p class="card-text">Firewalls protect your computer against hackers by enforcing a set of rules that determine what data should be let in and what should be excluded.</p>
  </div>
</div>
